<DocsLayout title="Monitoring & Iteration" description="Go live, monitor payments and integrations, and reflect on API verification.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Monitoring & Iteration</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Marcus signed off. Client feedback is fixed and deployed. Vinyl Vault is live — people can browse records, search by artist or genre, add to cart, pay with Stripe, and find the physical shop on the map.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4">What to monitor</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Vinyl Vault has more moving parts than Clay & Co. Payment processing and third-party integrations add monitoring requirements:</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Stripe dashboard</h3>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Successful vs failed payments</strong> — a sudden spike in failures means something broke</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Webhook delivery</strong> — Stripe shows whether webhooks were delivered and accepted. Failed webhooks mean orders aren't being confirmed</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Disputed payments</strong> — rare for a small store, but worth monitoring</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Error logs and order records</h3>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">API failures</strong> — 500 errors, database connection issues, third-party service outages</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Order consistency</strong> — do orders in your database match payments in Stripe? If they diverge, webhook handling is broken</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Inventory accuracy</strong> — are stock counts correct after purchases?</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Google Maps</h3>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>API usage in Google Cloud Console — stay within the free tier</li>
    <li>Embed still loads and shows the correct pin location</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Sentry error tracking</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Open your Sentry dashboard. If there are errors, you'll see them grouped with stack traces, affected users, and frequency. This is your first real monitoring tool — it tells you things are broken before users complain.</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Unhandled exceptions</strong> — Sentry captures these automatically. A spike in errors after deployment means something broke.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Error grouping</strong> — Similar errors are grouped together. One entry might represent hundreds of occurrences of the same bug.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Stack traces</strong> — Each error shows exactly where it happened in your code. No more guessing from vague user reports.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Release tracking</strong> — If you tag releases, Sentry shows which deployment introduced the error.</li>
  </ul>

