  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Reflect: API hallucination</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is the core reflection for P4. Think honestly about the verification process:</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">About hallucination detection</h3>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>How many times did Claude write incorrect API calls? What was wrong — method names, parameters, response fields?</li>
    <li>How did you catch the errors? By reading the docs, by testing, or by hitting a runtime error?</li>
    <li>How long did API verification take compared to verifying non-API code?</li>
    <li>Did the CLAUDE.md instruction about citing documentation URLs help? Would you write it differently next time?</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">About the verification habit</h3>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>Did you verify every API call, or did you start skipping some because "it looks right"?</li>
    <li>Were you faster at verification by the end of the project than at the start?</li>
    <li>Would you trust AI-generated API integration code without checking the docs? Why or why not?</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">About the process</h3>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-6">
    <li>Did isolating API tickets in the backlog make verification easier?</li>
    <li>Was the backlog ordering right — core features before integrations?</li>
    <li>How did Marcus's scope question compare to Sarah's in P3? Was it easier to handle the second time?</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>The key insight:</strong> The Stripe docs are more reliable than any AI. The skill isn't knowing Stripe — it's knowing to check. Every third-party API you integrate in the future follows the same pattern: AI generates the code, you verify against the official documentation. The API changes. The habit stays the same.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: error tracking & APM</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Sentry is an error tracker — it captures exceptions and tells you what broke. APM (Application Performance Monitoring) goes further, tracking response times, database queries, and system health. Many tools do both.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Sentry</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Error tracking with stack traces, release tracking, and alerting. Free tier is generous. What you're using in this project. Also offers basic performance monitoring.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Bugsnag</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Similar to Sentry — error monitoring with grouping and alerts. Strong mobile SDK support. Popular in iOS and Android development.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Rollbar</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Error tracking with a focus on real-time alerting and deploy tracking. Integrates well with CI/CD pipelines.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Datadog APM</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Full APM platform — traces requests across services, monitors infrastructure, and tracks errors. Enterprise-grade. Expensive but comprehensive.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">New Relic</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">One of the original APM tools. Monitors everything from server metrics to browser performance. Free tier available. Heavy but powerful.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Honeybadger</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Simple error tracking aimed at small teams. Less feature-rich than Sentry but easier to set up and understand.</span></p></div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">Start with error tracking (Sentry). When you need to understand why something is slow — not just broken — you'll move toward full APM. Most teams start with Sentry and add Datadog or New Relic as they scale.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="border border-border rounded-lg p-6 my-8 bg-bg-subtle text-center">
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Show someone</h3>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-3">Open the store on your phone. Search for a record. Add it to the cart. Go through checkout with a test card. Show someone the order confirmation page. Then open the Stripe dashboard and show them the payment.</p>
    <p class="text-text-secondary font-medium">"I built an online store with real payment processing. I directed AI to write the code and verified every API call against the official documentation."</p>
    <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-3">That last part matters. Anyone can get AI to generate Stripe code. Knowing that you need to check it — and knowing how — is the difference between code that works and code that fails when a customer tries to pay.</p>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
